<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-02-26T10:40:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-02-26T10:40:00-05:00" n="802" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d802">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">839.00 Revolutions/18: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Dominican Republic</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Curtis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Santo
                                        Domingo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-02-26T11:00:00-04:40">February 26, 1930—11
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 2:45 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>20. The British Chargé d’Affaires informs me that a small British warship
                            will arrive here within 20 hours.</p>
                        <pb facs="0801" n="703" xml:id="pg_703"/>
                        <p>The commander of the revolutionary forces and the Government civil
                            authorities are showing apparently sincere desire to maintain order but
                            there are great numbers of idle, irresponsible persons in the city and
                            the situation remains delicate. Trujillo is still holding the fortress
                            nominally for the Government.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Curtis</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>